<header>
	<h1>Data Views</h1>
</header>

<section class="dash-content-section">
	<h2>What are Data Views?</h2>
	<p>
	Data Views let you pre-compute data structures from your collections using Twig templates.
	Instead of querying and transforming data every time a page loads, a Data View runs your
	Twig template once and caches the result. You can then access the pre-built data instantly
	via <code>cms.view.get('view-id')</code> in any template.
	</p>

	<h2>How They Work</h2>
	<ol>
		<li><strong>Write a Definition:</strong> Create a Twig template that builds up a <code>data</code> variable
		using <code>cms.collection.objects()</code>, <code>cms.collection.search()</code>, or any other CMS functions.</li>
		<li><strong>Set Dependencies:</strong> Choose which collections the view depends on. When objects in those
		collections are created, updated, or deleted, the view is automatically queued for rebuild.</li>
		<li><strong>Use the Data:</strong> Access the pre-computed result anywhere with <code>cms.view.get('view-id')</code>.</li>
	</ol>

	<h2>Example</h2>
	<p>A simple view that counts blog posts and collects their titles:</p>
	<pre><code>{% verbatim %}{% set posts = cms.collection.objects('blog') %}
{% set data = {
  "count": posts|length,
  "titles": posts|column('title')
} %}{% endverbatim %}</code></pre>
	<p>Then in any template: <code>{% verbatim %}{{ cms.view.get('my-view').count }}{% endverbatim %}</code></p>

	<h2>Job Queue Required</h2>
	<p>
	Data Views rebuild automatically when their dependent collections change. These rebuilds are processed
	through the <a href="utils/jobqueue">Job Queue</a>. Make sure your job queue is running so
	that views stay up to date.
	</p>
</section>
